I've combed through the docs, but I'm getting stuck with types when performing a partial update. It seems like the type of the partition key is different in the `ToolboxItem` returned from `UpdateItemCommand` than `FormattedItem`.

Here is my usage below.

Schema and entity definition:
```ts
import { Table, item, string, Entity, FormattedItem, InputItem } from "dynamodb-toolbox";

export const ClientTable = new Table({
  name: `${process.env.TABLE_NAME_PREFIX}-client`,
  partitionKey: {
    name: "clientId",
    type: "string",
  },
  documentClient,
});

export const clientSchema = item({
  clientId: string().key(),
  name: string(),
});

export const ClientEntity = new Entity({
  name: "Client",
  schema: clientSchema,
  table: ClientTable,
  entityAttribute: false,
});

export type UpdateClient = InputItem<typeof ClientEntity, { mode: "update" }>;
export type FormattedClient = FormattedItem<typeof ClientEntity>;
```

Update:
```ts
const partialUpdate: UpdateClient = {
  clientId: "test-client-id",
  name: "new name"
};

const { ToolboxItem } = await ClientEntity.build(UpdateItemCommand)
    .item(partialUpdate)
    .send();

const formattedClient: FormattedClient = ToolboxItem;
```

The last line throws type error TS2322 that the type of property `clientId` is incompatible between ToolboxItem and FormattedClient, because the type of ToolboxItem.clientId is
```ts
string | GET<[ref: Paths<ItemSchema<{
  clientId: StringSchema<{
    required: "always"
    key: true
}>
```

and the type of FormattedClient.clientId is 
```ts
GET<[ref: Paths<ItemSchema<{
  clientId: StringSchema<{
    required: "always"
    key: true
}>
```
I tried parsing the partial update before the UpdateItemCommand (`clientSchema.build(Parser).parse(clientUpdates, { mode: "update" })`), but that didn't seem to have an impact on the return type. I also tried adding `.options({ returnValues: "ALL_NEW" })` to the UpdateItemCommand chain and using the Attributes returned, but the type was the same.


I was hoping that DynamoDB Toolbox would handle all the type conversions, but do I need to do a cast somewhere? Any guidance on best practices is appreciated!

